author: @user-dr2yz8um3d
text:
1 year old!


23 years since the first attempt to adapt the infamous fantasy board game and Hollywood tries their hand again 
The original dungeons and dragons was a complete misfire that got so many things wrong from the casting to the acting to the effects 
Even worse was an outdated black stereotype character that didn't help 

This is truly a more fun and solid adaptation of the beloved board game with plenty of references and inside knowledge for fans from the strategies to even the cartoon series
It's very lively, colorful, very detailed when it comes to the creatures whether cgi or practical effects, and the actors make the material very light hearted
There really is though so much lore, backstory, and exposition to pay attention to 
The fun stuff doesn't exactly kick in until the last half when the High Sun tournament starts making it actually feel like a game 
Some tighter pacing would‚Äôve helped to get to the more flashier parts 
Yet plenty of laughs and remarkable chemistry of Chris Pine, Michelle Rodriguez, Sophia Lillis, and Justice Smith make for a smooth ride 
Think of this like Monty Python meets ‚ÄòPrincess Bride‚Äô 
The filmmakers if they play their cards right so to speak might have a franchise on their hands given how much love they have for the source material

author: @fornlike
text:
This film is very beautiful, it is funny and it is the one that succeeds best in the area where the vast majority of films fail: creativity. He manages to surprise the viewer with the unexpected way he reuses elements that he has previously clearly presented. In general, to thwart complex situations, for lack of ingenuity and imagination, authors decree things, project unknown elements into action...
For example in "Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice" it was decreed that Superman would be more resistant to the effects of kryptonite in order to defeat Doomsday. In Spectre, it was decreed that Ernst Stavro Blofeld would take James Bond's watch for a trivial thing, which is completely inconsistent. We find this logic in all the blockbusters. This film is the one where this mistake is made the least. In it we see characters facing difficult situations and using inventive ways to solve them. That's why I consider it the most successful blockbuster. From a cinematographic point of view, I place it above all Marvel films, DC, the Matrix saga (my favorite cinematic project), Lord of the Rings, Harry Potter,... In short! The most serious, inventive cinematic work I've seen so far and I'm all the happier, because finally the legendary Dungeons & Dragons saga is cinematically honored. Finally, a real nice cinematic surprise!

author: @arkane5260
text: I've been a Dungeons and Dragons fan since the early 90s. I've played all the games since then so it was nice to mention things like Baldurs Gate and Neverwinter, although it usually wasn't much more than a reference. The writers came out early and said they had fun emasculating the male characters in this movie. That was an early indication that this would be a movie focusing more on social politics rather than entertainment. Unfortunately, that was correct. Almost all the men here are physically weak and idiots whereas all the women are strong and intelligent. One girl with no armor or weapons beats up 20+ soldiers in full plate mail and throws them around like rag dolls. Even the dragon was made to be an obese idiot. One guy was an actual housewife. This movie could have been fantastic but instead its just an advertisement in diversity, inclusion and woman power. Snow flakes rejoice.

author: @dimetrodon2250
text: I was blown away by how accurate to DnD this movie was. It feels like a love letter to DnD made by people who play DnD. I was expecting the usual watered down "made for general audiences" MCU style film and instead we got what was essentially a DnD campaign in movie form. Everything from the locations, to the spells, to the monsters, to the magic items all perfectly represented DnD. The film also utilizes show-dont-tell in a way that most Hollywood movies struggle with due to their need for as general of an audience as possible. Nobody needs to explain the bag of holding, or what a displacer beast is, or how breaking concentration affects certain spells, unless the explanation itself is relevant to the plot. Even when they do explain things, it never feels clunky or out of place.

author: @darrinwebber4077
text:
At 60.years old now... I played AD&D 2nd Edition... Mystara... Forgotten Realms...etc during my 20's. Then, in my 30's...I ran campaign with the variant Birthright rules. 
 My greatest character was a half-orc multi-class Paladin/Cleric/Sorcerer named Noot.
While his development was slow...very slow... eventually even god's feared him.
(Even when running Birthright rules... I ran him as my personal character. The player group thought he was an NPC...but he had to follow every rule and I made "possible actions" lists based on his alignment and such...and rolled dice to be fair and not let my knowledge as the campaign operator give him an unfair advantage.
I don't play anymore. My micronation is my hobby now. 
My nephew now carries the D&D flame online.
And loves it as I did.

author: @hiair
text: The story is in the Manual. If I played ‚ÄúHungry Hungry Hippos‚Äù with my friends in a deathly serious way, is it right to assume that everyone else did the same and therefore the movie must be that way? Stop saying that making this thing ‚Äúsuperdumb‚Äù was the ‚Äúright thing‚Äù because that‚Äôs how you played D&D with your friends, I don‚Äôt believe you did, specially with those $u$piciou$ly $hort comments and the pronouns in your profiles that are used by people that hate nerd stuff. Just like any other board game, everyone has a different experience every single time you played it, even if you do it with the same group of friends. Movies are meant to be for the general audience that didn‚Äôt played them exactly like you did, and quite probably didn‚Äôt even played it at all. BUT there is one element that is totally objective and every single person that ever played the game experienced exactly the same way as everyone else, The MANUAL, The MANUAL which is not subjective as your defense is. Every detail about the characters and their world is in the manual and is written seriously, there is no goofy ‚Äúcomedy‚Äù in it all. What they are doing here is mocking the seriousness of the source material from their very subjective and narcissistic point of view. If they had followed the manual instead, or the books, or comics that were written afterwards, they could had filled the expectations of the biggest part of the audience. That‚Äôs why your statement is utter stupid. You still want things that don‚Äôt belong to you, to reflect you, because you are incapable to like them the way they originally are. Narcissist.

author: @bradhilton2283
text: Now this movie looks good (Unlike" Babylon " worse pice of crap ever )  I mean the first dungeons and dragons movie was ok , the one with Waynes brothers and Jermey irons, I certainly enjoyed that   . But the Dungeons& Dragons universe has tons of books that are great for television that could lead into major motion pictures. Such as Greyhawk , DarkSun, Spell Jammer , DRAGON LANCE(One of my Personal favourites ) Forgotten Realms And RAVEN LOFT (AN OTHER FAVOURITE) . IMAGINE going to the Imax and watching two waring armies in the sky of dragons and their riders battle each other with 6' foot long dragon lances . Dragons of metallic gold and silver vs Dragons of Black and Red grappling each other as they crash into a mountain side . Armies of reptilian Draconian men that turn too stone and explode once they are killed as weapons used to kill them are fused too them . Hey that jacket of Criss pine looks kind of interesting , Imagine limited release clothing in conjunction  upon the release of the movie . Thats video games or a friendly meet up for a table top of  d&d for coffee and snacks on a Saturday once or twice a month . Now good story matters and dragon lance has been on the new york times best selling list several times . Good story is the cake , special effects and big name actors are just the icing . I mean every one is sick of 8 mile , boys in the hood and straight outta Compton , No one wants too see that crap or here about the shit anymore "Ohhh boo hoo, hooo ...I'm only 12% poor me " . But something like this will take your mind off the rat race of the week and "Entertain you" as well as give you something too look forward to as the "Entertainment industry should" , not piss you off. But if the studios started too turn their head in this direction" $$$$ ". There is "Dragons of Autumn Twilight " released in the fall of course , "Dragons of Winter Night " the following Christmas season and "Dragons of Spring Dawning " that could be relased the proceeding spring of the next year . There lots of television shows that could fill in the gaps between the movies , Such as Kaz the Minotaur . Not to mention  Theo ironfeld wich would be a great role for the rock or Jason mamoa as the charter is black . There is also "Vampire of The Mist" with might be a good fit for Robert Pattison .Witch is from the Ravenloft franchise that ties into other mentioned franchises . So there is a lot of things you can do with this dungeons and dragons universe  . I mean lets face it the last three Star Wars movies blew at the box office and Indiana jones ...Ok there old timer , don't get you hip out of joint . But this is something kinda fresh and new , with a built in audience . So this could franchise generate a lot of money both at the big screen and the small screen , But the key word is "Entertainment " unlike the nfl and Black lives matters .

author: @terryrobbins5977
text: I know it‚Äôs a D&D movie and not really the medieval era but it kinda is in a big way we have swords, peasants, castles, kings, etc. etc. You get the point. So, with that said it bothers me that Chris Pine is talking with an American accent. A British, Spanish, Italian, or any other accent of the medieval era would have been better and believable except for a modern-day American accent a la ‚Äúdude‚Äù man. It just pulls me right out of the movie. It‚Äôs like making a movie about the Italian mafia in New York City and everyone has British accents.  ‚ÄúI say cheers, forgetta about it my good man‚Äù. Can you imagine Gandolf having a New Jersey accent? Think how ridiculous Lady Galadriel would sound if she talked like Rosie Perez?  Don‚Äôt get me wrong I like Rosie Perez I think she‚Äôs a great actor but I don‚Äôt think a New York accent would work well in any British tea bag dramas. Some accents are just too contemporary to fit into a period piece film set in era that long ago. With all that said I really hope it‚Äôs a good film because that last D&D film in 2000 was not.

author: @AstroPsych_
text:
List of all the D&D content I could find (based on 5e):

[0:22] Black Chromatic Dragon using Acid Breath
[0:43] The red robed figure _really_ looks like the Lich from the Monster Manual
[0:47] Some kind of spell being cast. Based on everything being shattered around the caster, I'm guessing something like _Thunderwave_ or _Shatter_ . The Bard appears to be moving normally through slow motion, so he may be under the effect of _Haste_ or something.
[1:06] Looks like _Thunderwave_ being cast from that crown (also, casting from a magic item rather than your class), ignoring whatever is happening on a larger scale across the city (maybe amplified somehow?)
[1:10] Druid wildshaping from a horse to an Owlbear
[1:25] Bronze or Brass dragon (teal + gold coloration)
[1:26] Druid passes through _Dimension Door_ (not on the Druid spell list, but it's a minor detail, and maybe she didn't cast it)
[1:28] The underdark?
[1:30] _Green Flame Blade_ spell
[1:36] Some kind of lightning spell ( _Witch Bolt_ is my guess, could also be many others)
[1:37] Fireball (possibly from the _Fireball_ spell, possibly just from a catapult) connects with the _Shield_ spell. Technically wouldn't work within rules, since _Shield_ raises your AC and _Fireball_ needs a saving throw, but it's still cool.
[1:42] Mimic!
[1:45] Gelatinous Cube + Displacer Beast. Love that they're using all of these classic monsters straight out of the manual, with designs practically straight out of the book.
[1:46] Probably _Magic Missile_, though technically in the rules _Magic Missile_ is an automatic hit
[1:47]  _Misty Step_ 
[1:48] Adult Red or Brass dragon, from the Fire breath. Lighting makes it hard to tell.

text: Dungeons & Dragons... and again they pick some random world with random generic characters... and there is so much famous material already there... WHY not take the Drizzt Saga into account? Or Neverwinter... yeah from the massive succesful computer game Neverwinter Nights. The powers, wealth, and enchanted loot that he gathered across endless hours of imaginary adventures are now made real. The catch? author: @Vrinara
text:
Having watched the trailer now. Well. I think the music isn't right for the trailer. Now hear me out on this cause that doesn't mean the trailer is bad. I've seen a lot of movie trailers that have put some sort of music in their trailers, let it be rock, rap, pop, hip hop. You get it, and have failed. I get that the music is supposed to hype us up, but it really shouldn't have been used for the first trailer.

Now what can I say about the trailer? I like the creatures they are using. They are your stereotypical creatures you might use for a D&D Campaign. Which is a good thing. They aren't all the popular choices dms go for. Which is a good thing. I like the party....ish. Michelle Rodrigez playing the strong woman type is typical, but I can't see her playing any other character (Or class), And that's not me marking on her. She's awesome and fits the role perfectly. Chris Pine is fucking perfect as the sleazy bard. I also love the fact that they are focusing on the bard a little bit over the loner type characters most of these movies have. And to be fair, most bards are the leaders of parties so it fits. Overall, Besides the music. looks good. Won't get my hopes up, but I may go see it next year.

author: @darianashkevron9969
text:
I'm worried that you're playing this way too seriously. If this trailer is anything to go by, you're making a generic fantasy movie, and very fundamentally NOT a D&D movie, or any RPG for that matter. If this trailer is accurate, this movie is going to fail HARD.

A true D&D movie is going to be, at best, a comedy action film. Not an action comedy, comedy MUST come first.

A true D&D movie needs stuff like a character dying, followed by the group meeting a character played by the same actor joining them in the next scene (preferably of a similar class). A true D&D movie needs stuff like the characters yelling at the gods that the hordes of enemies they're facing is unfair, followed immediately by one of the enemies fumbling a wand of illusions and most of them disappearing.

A D&D movie would be far more than just the setting, it requires OOC idiocy.

10 Of The World's Funniest One Liners Ever!

1. I didn't fight my way to the top of the food chain to be a vegetarian.

This is because you have sinned against God. Let's see if that's true: Have you ever lied (even once)? Ever stolen (anything)? Jesus said, "Whoever looks upon a woman to lust after her, has committed adultery already with her in his heart." Ever looked with lust? If you have said "Yes" to these three questions, by your own admission, you are a lying, thieving, adulterer at heart; and we've only looked at three of the Ten Commandments. How will you do on Judgment Day? Will you be innocent or guilty? You know that you will be guilty, and end up in Hell. That's not God's will. He provided a way for you to be forgiven. He sent His Son to take your punishment: "God commended His love toward us, in that, while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us." Jesus then rose from the dead and defeated death. God promises everlasting life to all those who confess and forsake their sins, and trust in Jesus Christ. Please do that today . . . you may not have tomorrow. See John 14:21 for a wonderful promise. author: @phelanwolf6747
text:
Thieves as main characters in a D&D movie...again. Maybe that is just...American...
This is a lost opportunity to show the epic story of characters with depth, values and strugles like that of a certain Drow, a Paladin knight like Huma or unlike twins and dragon riders. And you can still have some comedy moments but instead the trailer shows a comedy movie with some D&D references, sure the costumes and effects look great but story and characters are doubtful. Worldending stories are also usually bad in such a context, in movies AND pen & paper RPGs.

author: @Paladin585
text: I mean, this could do well, I just don't see how a Dungeons and Dragons movie is supposed to work. D&D at its heart is cooperative story telling, effectively most fantasy movies could be looked at as D&D movies, just lacking the players. This could be good, but it's ultimately just a fantasy story with references to the game. If anything is going to make something an actual D&D movie, it's gotta incorporate the players as well.

author: @Draeka
text: Looks terrible.  They are literally remaking the original flop of a D&D movie.  With the same formula.  Actors who don't know and don't care about the source material.  Remixed 70s rock that befits a car commercial.  Cringe level comical timing and dad jokes.  Bollywood level CGI.  Talk about schtick layers on schtick.  It is kind of shocking too.  Especially since there is literally a half centuries worth of D&D fantasy lore.  Picking nearly any module and turning it into a script would produce a fantastic plot.  In a funny way the best D&D live action content right now is actually Stranger Things.  The characters and story are more befitting a true D&D campaign.  When an actual D&D movie is served up we always get a mid-page cartoon strip.  I have zero hope for this film.

author: @mazurkian
text: I think a lot of people think of DND has a very high-fantasy lord of the rings game. And it CAN be, but it's often a band of morally questionable misfits making terrible decisions and stumbling into a plot that's above their pay grade and then trying to become heroes. I hope that the writing and plot is decent, but I am hopeful that it will at least represent what DnD looks and feels like it the minds of the people who play it. I don't care if they get things "mechanically" wrong but I appreciate that they are at least representing the different classes and actually have monsters from the game. I got really excited when I saw the displacer beast and gelatinous cube, more so than the owlbear. It was cool seeing how an owlbear might move though.

author: @1003JustinLaw
text:
Few things:
- First of all what is that dragon? Tar Dragon? And what's with the other dragons in the trailer? The derpy white dragon and the black dragon that lives in fire? What?
- Besides the dragon BS, I'm glad they're using actual monsters from the game, glad to see the Displacer Beast, Gelatinous Cube, and Mimic getting some big screen time. That said, dodging into a Gelatinous Cube is a REALLY bad idea, I'd personally rather eat the Displacer Beast hit instead.
- Also, and I realize that I'm rules lawyering here, that (I'm going to assume) Druid girl shapeshifting into an Owlbear... Owlbears are monstrosities, neither Wild Shape nor the Polymorth spell can turn someone into a monstrosity, only beasts, so unless she's casting Shapechanger, the bloody 9th-level spell, there's no way she's transforming into an Owlbear. But if she's got access to 9th-level spells, what's she doing getting arrested (I think) by a bunch of normal soldiers? And if you have access to Shapechanger, why Owlbear? The minimum level Druids can have 9th-level spells is 17th level, Shapechanger allows you to transform into any creature whose CR is equal or less than your level, so at the minimum she could transform into a CR 17 thing. What has a CR of 17? Oh I don't know, ADULT RED AND GOLD DRAGONS just to name some examples! An Owlbear's CR is 3, what a waste of a Shapechanger spell if that's actually what it was.
- Next, what is that magic barrier spell? I can't for the life of me think of any Abjuration spell that does whatever it just did.
- And finally, that Mimic, it's not a chest with a tongue, it's a blob disguised as a chest, so it won't clunk into the wall.

That said, I certainly hope the movie does justice to actual D&D and these surface-level complaints I have are just teething problems for cinema's first foray into D&D, at least first in the sense that it's not going to paint D&D as either a Satanic devil-worshipping cult initiation ritual or some corruptive influence that causes psychological problems in the young (like that Mazes and Monsters movie starring Tom Hanks).

author: @rbbecker73
text:
You know what stands out to me the most? The fact that I immediately spotted 5 monsters in this trailer that are relatively unique to D&D, rather than just generic fantasy/mythology creatures. You've got the owlbear (obviously), mimic, displacer beast, gelatinous cube, and a dragon with a non-fire breath weapon. (Black dragon with an acid line breath attack?)

Also, the shield effect that looks like what Eric the Cavalier used to do in the old D&D cartoon.

And lots of other stuff that may or may not be unique to D&D, or just come from generic fantasy. Speaking of which, is satyr a player race in D&D these days?

author: @kenjiwa5895
text:
Interesting trailer, which leaves me in two minds.

First what I struggle with: 
‚Ä¢	The modern phrases ("Here's the thing") and intonations, which always grate as they seem to come straight out of a Californian teenage movie
‚Ä¢	The ensemble cast that looks a little like an exercise in box-ticking and includes some pretty tiresome clich√©s (the hard-as-nails female character WITH THE DEEP VOICE and attitude, yawn).
‚Ä¢	The fact the characters don‚Äôt really feel appealing. I realise in an ensemble cast you can‚Äôt like them all, but I don‚Äôt relate to any of these. Compare to something like Fell's Five, where characters were a lot less clich√©d and way more appealing.
I suppose I am too old for these, but it‚Äôs a shame to cater to one demographic, rather than be canny and offer something to all age groups and personality types. 

What I really, really like:
‚Ä¢	The worlds, creatures and lore are stunning. 
‚Ä¢	Contrasting environments, amazing beasts and secondary characters.
‚Ä¢	Special effects are genuinely superb and make my heart leap like when I was a teenager and spent hours painting little figurines, playing RPGs or reading fantasy books. 

Not sure whether I‚Äôll go and see it. I fear the Netflix vibe may overcome any pleasure I would derive as an RPG and fantasy fan. But then I may be missing on truly captivating escapism because of a few annoying characters who may turn out to be likeable in the full version.
Time will tell.

author: @Seldinor
text:
I hope it is fun, but as a fan of old D&D I don't like the modern zany Star-wars-cantina pseudo-modern setting and characters, like the tv show of Critial Role.

I know I will be in the minority saying this, but the comic-anime style crazy looking characters and worlds full of color and modern trappings of 3rd edition onwards are for me really goofy and nonsensical. I prefer the grounded art style of 1st and 2nd edition, the attention to medieval sources to describe it's world and themes and the feeling of danger it gave. Now D&D feels like a theme park ride: safe and mediocre fun for everyone.


 If the movie is trying to be a comedy I have no problem with that, but if it tries to represent a D&D world I just won't dig it.

author: @icelandia4
text:
I love DnD - I've spent years in it, roleplaying in NWN, playing the tabletop game, and eventually becoming the all-time DM for my group - and I'll gladly take a film, but I can't help but think this has already failed. 

Everything about this trailer screams an attempt to copy the vibe of the superhero-avenger films, which I actually like, but it's not what I want or expect from DnD. The cast seems uninspired and generic, the antagonists are insipid, the plot may as well just be an excuse to have an adventure. 

I don't think it will be a bad film, but it will be definitely a very mediocre and forgettable film. The kind of movie you watch because it's there and you will not learn or remember anything.

author: @FictionRaider007
text:
Looks better than the 2000 film but that's not exactly difficult (although I'll personally love it in an ironic way even if only for Jeremy Irons hammy acting). Given D&D's rise in popularity recently they've made sure to get some of the more iconic things unique to the tabletop in there (displacer beasts, owlbears, mimics, etc.) which helps more firmly set it as an actual D&D property rather than any other fantasy film. I'll obviously reserve judgement until I see the film but there isn't any major warning signs in the trailer.

Things I'd want to see in a D&D movie but probably won't:
- Cuts to the "real life" players sat around the table telling the story, even if only once or twice.
- One of the characters dies and then the same actor shows up playing a new character that joins the party in the next scene (as the player's "new character").
- Characters actually using legitimate tactics and moves from the game, maybe even abusing some of them that players also overuse (e.g.: flanking for advantage).
- References to stuff from the older editions before 5e for the die hards.

So... a party of all humans, but one tiefling that still looks 98% human? Seriously? That's it? All the things they could have done and she just has tiny horns? And the face of your party is Captain Kirk. Nah. Not cool.  Pretty graphics but I think this is going to suck.

#1 comment everyone is making: "This looks like a real game!" That is our entire standard for a D&D movie. And having money this time for graphics. 

And anyone that's saying "Finally, another movie, after more than 20 years!" I have sad news for you. There's a massive list of B and C movies they never stopped making, this entire time.

author: @Stone7C1
text:
and here we have the perfect example of another movie that should have been animation instead of live action.

what is it with hollywood producers trying to cram these stories into the wrong format? live action comic book and game adaptations rarely ever look even halfway decent because its really hard to translate the medium onto real actors. so why are you repeatedly trying to smash your heads into the wall and keep repeating the same mistake instead of doing something different?

despite what a lot of people say here in the comments that it doesnt look terrible, this looks really fucking dumb and could have looked great if it was fully animated. half of the movie is going to be CGI anyway for the kind of action scenes they are trying to do because theyre really just impossible to do without.

the problem with CGI overloaded live action movies like this here is that one they age really terribly, and two the quality of the animations here doesnt even look good by todays standarts already. imagine they had just made this entire movie in a classic animated 2D format and didnt try to cramp greenscreens and real live actors into this uncanny valley of awkward action scenes where theyre shadow boxing with obvious CGI together.

compare this trailer to the legend of vox machina which is also a modern DnD adaptation to screen, imagine for a second what this movie would look like in a similar format, and youll understand what i mean.

author: @SidewaysBurnouts
text: i can tell from the poor shot choices this is doomed, i like the idea, but the execution is pretty lame. It feels like a toy commerical. Bad casting, bad aesthetics. A D&D movie should feel like being in mordor on the volcano for 90 mins. Where is the dungeons? There should be more monsters, more death, more gloom and fire lit terror. Look at movies that crash and burn, Jungle Cruise, 47 Ronin, they all want to be the bad mummy remake, or clash of the titans. Leaning into cgi, hipster casting, modern hair cuts are all bad choices. You should have something that looks like Agguire The Wrath of God, tired and scared knights, covered in mud and blood, castles that looks like old D&D art work... in fact thats what i really mean, has this director/producer even seen D&D art work or books? How could you think characters wearing gel and hairspray would be a correct choice for a mideval movie? Id rather watch Mazes and Monsters or Beastmaster or never ending story or williow or ladyhawke or dragonslayer.

author: @Laoruperteen18
text:
okay, you know what? considering how whacky and stupid and downright fucky-uppy a typical D&D campaign goes, with its players, and how D&D tends to generally go, im absolutely down for this kind of style of film for D&D.

With a more comical setting with a charming cast that is pretty much playing the role of a typical D&D team as you would have in an actual game, this 100% works, because then you dont risk pissing off your target audience when you mess up the lore or important characters, just like a real game of D&D, its all flexible, and this truly feels like we are following a real life D&D party, hell i wouldnt even be mad that at the end of the movie we find out that it WAS an IRL group of players playing out this movie on tabletop and ending it with a "GG guys, good session" :D

author: @realitycheck1018
text: To the people below who have obviously never played DD.  An owlbear is not something a wizard can transform into.  A thief cannot cast spells, and only the highest levelled thieves with maxed out ability scores can handle even the weakest of rods staves and wands. Scrolls have to be read allowed, not held, and generally take a turn, which is 6 minutes not 6 seconds. In aDD, it's actually an hour.  And finally, in the players handbook, the number 1 cliche meme is, "there is NO honor among thieves." The theif is the guy the party brings along, reluctantly, because they need him to open locks and disarm traps in ancient runes.  This tends to cause paladins to kill them when they commit evil acts or lose their powers when they don't. It's a major contention point in DD designed to cause inner party turmoil for the purpose of social interaction at the table. DD is not about a party of theives.

text: This is just angering.  First, I was a DM for some 30 yrs and have hosted many thousands of games.  I have even played at Gygax's table at gencon.  While I  am happy to finally see a descent production of a DD movie this is still not right. The last movie was centered on a thief, or what could be more described as a fighter/thief and it's successor had the cleric killed off right att he beginning.  I chalked this up to production costs and lack of technology.  However, we have Superman flying around now and all sorts of visual effects today.  DD is not about a bunch of thieves...it is about a party of heroic adventurers battling a force of evil or braving some ancient ruins to gather power to battle some force of evil. When will they make an actual DD movie that features the party as it is intended to be?  A fighter, paladin, ranger, cleric, wizard and thief.  One theif, not 5, as they would die right off without a healer.  All mmo players know this, in fact, all video game players know this as video games are based off of DD.

author: @zpardus
text:
Good they're not pulling punches with the lore. Past D&D movies have been afraid to do anything that might confuse non-D&D players.
But here, we have a black dragon breathing lore-accurate acid instead of the fire people would expect, a druid shapeshifting around because it's just what they do, and a six-legged panther with tentacles coming out of its back because that's what displacer beasts are supposed to look like, obviously.
And if someone's not a player? They don't need to get all the creature and spell references to follow a fantasy adventure plot. They never did.

author: @Axel-zc6xj
text: This... THIS is perfect. Honestly, with how hollywood wants diversity in cast, "strong female characters", etc. it is tough to force those things in universes with existing characters that just DONT have that. No one wants a caucasian black panther. However, DnD is all about choice. A female barbarian that, although with the classic female body, tossing men around like ragdolls? It is VERY real in DnD should a player want to do that! Race, gender, ethnicity, none of these have limits nor do they have to swap out characteristics to force them into roles they weren't designed for. AND NONE OF IT HAS TO BE FORCED IN PLACE OF GOOD WRITING! They can finally FOCUS on good writing! WHY DIDNT THEY DO THIS SOONER?!?!?!

author: @alle38
text:
I mean sure, it looks cool. But any high budget fantasy movie today will look cool. 
The problem is that it to any average person (that hasn't played dungeons & dragons) this just looks like a generic fantasy movie.
And slapping Dungeons & Dragons as the name is fine I guess, but this could've easily been named anything even close to fantasy and would probably still work.
I literally looked on a generic movie title generator and got some names this could've easily had:

Flameborn
Den of Monsters 
etc

I guess we will have to wait and see until it comes out whether or not it's actually any good, but my generic fantasy radar is going off when I see this, and that's not a good feeling.

text:
Super accurate creatures. Looks like I saw quite a few actually D&D spells and abilities (wild shape and was that Booming Blade???). Plot seems entirely on brand. Locations look awesome (Neverwinter???). Effects are great. Casting looks solid, and the characters all look like good examples of classic D&D tropes. Opting for a comedic tongue-in-cheek route so it doesn't take itself too seriously. Great production value and effects.
Uhhhh I was a total doubter but I am ENTIRELY on board with this! I hope it is as a great as this trailer looks!

author: @DeyaViews
text:
It has dungeons AND it has dragons, so it already nails that part! Also a bard, a druid, a barbarian(?), a paladin(?) and a wizard(?) party, with a plot resulting from accidentally "unleashing the greatest evil the world has ever known" AND involving a heist, with cameos from well-known D&D monsters like the gelatinous cube and the owlbear. Mark me down as excited.

author: @Badwolf0683
text:
Since so many people keep on commenting the same thing:

Circle of the Moon Druids can become Owl Bears. With DM approval and it's quite commonly allowed. The reason it isn't is because it's classified as a Monstrosity. Where Druid's wildshape into beasts. The reason for the Monstrosity is because the Owl Bear was originally labeled as a creation from a mad wizard.   Yet cannon changed it as a natural creature. However, the label wasn't changed. Depending on your DM you either use the older origins or the one more accepted in modern canon. So Yes a druid can wildshape into an owlbear. 

 "However, the oldest elves recalled that owlbears had been around for many millennia and a few fey claimed owlbears had always been found in the Feywild.[1] In fact, owlbears were brought into being by one of the creator races,[11] most likely the aearee". Their stat bloc is also very close to a strong Cave Bear with similarly low intelligence. 

So the reason the Owl Bear isn't allowed is due to the lore that it was created by a wizard. Yet recent lore suggests that was a myth and not the case.

I may be in the minority here but I didn't  like it at all. I was hoping for a more serious D&D movie, this looks exactly like the others before it, rogue/thief as protagonist, too focused on jokes/humor, modern soundtracks killing immersions, coming out of nowhere, the same "let's deal with the greatest evil the world has ever known" kind of plot... The D&D IP has become a joke anyway, so I guess this is appropriate, since WoTC can't make good use of it. I'm not going to put my money on this one, will watch it in a stream platform when it become available and if I have nothing better to do. 

What a disappointment.

text: Not going to lie, this looks leagues better than it's predecessors. That being said I wish they had stuck more to the cannon. It's great when they pay homage to their own product, like the mimic, the dragon's breath, etc., but the devil is always in the details. Druids can't wild shape into Owlbears. At least not per current ruleset. If monstrosities were on the table, oof, that would be horror for any DM. It's not a nitpick. It's just if you're going to do it, do it right.

author: @jedijones
text:
God, when will they STAHHHHP giving every single special effects action adventure movie the same tone as Guardians of the Galaxy? OVER IT! This brand is crying out for the dark, serious tone a director like Chris Nolan or Zack Snyder would bring to it. This rock and roll romp style feels as lame, tired, inappropriate and underwhelming as it did in Star Trek: Beyond and Thor: Ragnarok.

I kind of like how the cast is slightly fashioned after the look of the 1980s cartoon characters. They should've gone with that plot though. Because I cannot follow what's going on in this trailer at all. It needs to be grounded. Having these be kids coming from Earth trying to figure out this world would give the audience its entry point.

Love to see Sophia Lillis again though!

author: @SuperWoodgod
text:
I'm pleasantly surprised they're actually fully embracing the more out-there side of D&D, and that they've included the mimic, owlbear, and gelatinous cube.

Honestly, when I heard they were making a D&D movie, I was expecting something along the lines of a "serious fantasy" ala Game of Thrones (albeit with more powerful magic). I thought they'd only stick with the typical fantasy creatures like orcs, giants and dragons, which would be easier for a mainstream audience to swallow, and that they'd only hint at the weirder elements, or possibly wait until a sequel to introduce them. And I would have been fine with it if they decided to go that route, but what they're doing here is the kind of tone I wanted them to go with, so I'm definitely looking forward to this.

In terms of quality, I'm not expecting LOTR, but if they can manage something at least as decent as Pirates of the Caribbean or Guardians of the Galaxy, I'll be more than happy.
